The paper deals with the problem of top-$k$ selection over a large domain universe subject to user-level differential privacy, which is a problem that is relevant to several areas of computer science. The focus on differential privacy suggests that the paper could belong to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) or cs.LG (Machine Learning), which are sub-categories that often deal with privacy-preserving algorithms. The use of algorithms such as the exponential mechanism and report noisy max suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.IT (Information Theory), which is a sub-category that deals with the mathematical foundations of information processing. The fact that the paper considers the setting where the data domain is unknown suggests that it could belong to cs.DB (Databases) or cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which are sub-categories that deal with the storage and retrieval of data.
